 northern Ireland (Antrim and Derry)."],"variants":[{"name":"Sterling","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Stirling  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Starling</i>, <i>Sterling</i> (Old English <i>Stærling</i>), itself from the bird-name, whose use as a nickname may also be another source of the surname. Compare   Stare   2.","German: from Middle High German <i>sterlinc</i>, the name of a coin, hence probably a nickname for someone who paid that amount in rent."]}]},{"name":"Baroness","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Norwegian: old variant of <b>Bartnes</b> (and, in North America, probably also an altered form of this), a habitational name from Trøndelag, a form of Old Norse <i>burkn</i> ‘fern’ + <i>nes</i> ‘promontary, headland’.","In some cases possibly also an altered form of German   Bartmess  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bartmess","meanings":["American shortened form of German   Barthelmess  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Stirling","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire): habitational name from Stirling (Stirlingshire), earlier Scots <i>Strivilin</i> (or similar), a name of uncertain etymology. It is recorded in the 12th century as <i>Strevelin</i>, and is perhaps from a river name. This surname is also common in northern Ireland (Antrim and Derry)."],"variants":[{"name":"Sterling","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Stirling  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Starling</i>, <i>Sterling</i> (Old English <i>